The '''McIntire–Stennis Act of 1962''' (P.L. 87-788) makes funding available to the state agricultural experimental stations and to [[forestry school]]s and programs at the [[land grant colleges]] of agriculture for forestry research. The research covers such areas as [[reforestation]], woodlands and related [[Drainage basin|watershed]] management, outdoor recreation, [[wildlife habitat]]s and wood utilization. Many of the research projects are performed cooperatively with scientists at the laboratories of the [[United States Forest Service]].
[https://nifa.usda.gov/program/mcintire-stennis-capacity-grant McIntire-Stennis] funds are distributed by a formula that allocates $10,000 to each state, with 40% of the remainder being distributed according to a state’s share of the nation’s total commercial forest land, 40% according to the value of its timber cut annually, and 20% according to its state appropriation for forestry research.
